.s-vgTop2.s-vgBottom2
  %div{class: @presenter.pdf_term_title}
    Strike Price:
    %span.js-strikePriceText
    per share

  This is how much you will pay to exercise each option to purchase shares of  Common Stock. Common stock carries voting
  rights, but typically lacks the preferences and other special rights of preferred stock. Your strike price
  is based on the Company's latest 409A valuation, which is how private companies determine the fair market value of their
  common stock. If the Company's 409A valuation is higher when you leave than it is at the time of
  this letter, you may need to pay taxes on that gain. Exercising your options involves certain risks.  Depending on
  when you exercise your options, you may be subject to AMT on the gain recognized from the difference between your
  strike price and the share price determined by the Company's then-current 409A valuation.  Further, the Company
  may still later fail and your shares will be worth nothing.  Under U.S. securities laws, you are prohibited from
  selling your shares until you have held them for one year.  Realistically, however, you may not be able to sell
  those shares for many more years, until the Company is acquired or has an Initial Public Offering.  If the Company
  slumps and you sell your shares at a loss, you will still owe taxes on the gain recognized on the exercise date.

.s-vgTop2.s-vgBottom2
  %div{class: @presenter.pdf_term_title}
    Exercise Window:
    %span.js-exerciseWindowText
    after termination of employment.

  Your options will expire and may no longer be exercised following the exercise window.
  To retain Incentive Stock Option status, the options must be exercised within 90 days from the termination of your
  employment. If the options are not exercised within 90 days, they will automatically convert to Nonstatutory Stock Options
  and will no longer qualify for any preferential tax treatment accorded Incentive Stock Options.
  If you cannot afford to exercise the options and you do not Net Exercise (if allowed, see below), you will lose any ownership
  you have earned in the Company.

.s-vgTop2.s-vgBottom2
  %div{class: @presenter.pdf_term_title}
    Net exercise:
    %span.js-netExerciseText
  .js-netExerciseExplanation.js-no.u-hidden
    The Company does not have a net exercise program with respect to your options.
  .js-netExerciseExplanation.js-yes.u-hidden
    During your exercise window you can sell back to the Company a portion of the options for which the underlying
    shares have vested and use the resulting proceeds to exercise the remaining portion.  Your right to sell your
    options back to the Company is known as "net exercise".  The value per share of the options sold to the Company
    will be determined by the per share value according to the Company's latest 409A valuation minus your strike price.
    A net exercise means you won't have to pay out of pocket to receive shares of Common Stock, but it also means you
    will get fewer shares than you would if you used your own funds to exercise the options.
